ofessor of cultural studies & comparitive literature at university of minnesota lydia goehr panelist professor of philosophy at columbia university peter burgard moderator professor of german at harvard jessica payette panelist assistant professor of musicology at oakland university charles kronengold panelist assistant professor of musicology at stanford heather hadlock moderator associate professor of musicology at stanford daniel albright panelist professor of english at harvard david levin panelist professor of german studies and cinema and media studies at university of chicago mary ann smart moderator professor of musicology at uc berkeley gundula kreuzer panelist assistant professor of music history at yale ryan minor panelist professor of music history and theory at stony brook university adrian daub moderator assistant professor of german studies at stanford bryan gilliam panelist professor of musicology at duke stephen hinton panelist professor of music and by courtesy german at stanford the conference will take as its point of departure two peculiar facts that interpreting especially german opera with freud's theories in mind is not just productive but almost imperative at a particular moment of the form's history in particular after wagner and that psychoanalysis suddenly loses at least some of that heuristic purchase in the period after the first world war we hope to detail and interrogate the elective affinities between freudian psychoanalysis and fin de siecle opera in light of the severance of that affinity later in the twentieth century what unspoken factors subtended the uncanny felicity of freud as a paradigm for analyzing the operas of wagner pfitzner schreker zemlinsky braunfels etc and what factors fell away in the wake of schoenberg wolpe berg and weill for full program please visit https www stanford edu dept dlcl cgi bin web events opera after freud sponsored by the office of the associate dean of the humanities the division of literatures c